    {
      "id": "9778b7b3079865a83390758b8fd7743f48286946",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 256,
        "name": "Hiroya Nozaki",
        "email": "nozaki.hiroya@jp.fujitsu.com",
        "username": "HiroyaNozaki"
      },
      "date": "2012-06-06 08:17:20.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)\n\n",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "e805a127df26e740bf71ae315bf241df55b1b2a3",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 103,
        "name": "Zhenyu Xu",
        "email": "bobijam@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bobijam"
      },
      "date": "2012-06-11 04:48:24.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI have an idea to tackle with this race:\n\n1. add an bit obd_device member init_exp, initializing it to 0\n2. in lprocfs_exp_setup(), execute following psudo code sequence:\n\nobd->init_exp = 1;\nif (obd->stopping) {\n   obd->init_exp = 0;\n   exit;\n}\n...\nobd->init_exp = 0; \nexit the exp setup func on error or end of it\n\n3. in class_cleanup\n\nobd->obd_stopping = 1;\nwhile (obd->init_exp != 0) {\n    wait untill obd->init_exp == 0;\n}\n\nHiroya, what do you think of this idea?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "54d099e8370084441f0a38cd1beb7ce3eba77ebd",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 103,
        "name": "Zhenyu Xu",
        "email": "bobijam@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bobijam"
      },
      "date": "2012-06-11 04:52:06.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nafter second think, better change init_exp from a bit member to an atomic counter, increase it before start to setup a client exp, and descrease it before exit, thus multiple client setup won't be messed up.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "6c32c496c1eb1691848183e521c386cad9849b7a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 256,
        "name": "Hiroya Nozaki",
        "email": "nozaki.hiroya@jp.fujitsu.com",
        "username": "HiroyaNozaki"
      },
      "date": "2012-06-11 05:30:50.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThat's a good idea! But I think semaphore or something like that is better than atomic_int considering the case when multiple ll_ost_xx threads remain. Do you think so ?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "f25de77814af8be6085f56d29bc3a51ce616a38c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 103,
        "name": "Zhenyu Xu",
        "email": "bobijam@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bobijam"
      },
      "date": "2012-06-11 06:35:01.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nSince exp setup is a more frequent calling path than class cleanup, and a lighter mechanism should be used there, so I think atomic counter is better than semaphore, it's just my cents though.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "5da2524eb84fc6284034a0b6ec39fa93a84d0b79",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 256,
        "name": "Hiroya Nozaki",
        "email": "nozaki.hiroya@jp.fujitsu.com",
        "username": "HiroyaNozaki"
      },
      "date": "2012-06-11 06:38:08.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI got it! so I'll do the way.\n\n- add an atomic int, say init_exp, into obd_device\n- inc init_exp at the beginning of lprocfs_exp_setup()\n- dec init_exp at the end of lprocfs_exp_setup()\n- wait and see until init_exp is zero, in class_cleanup()",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "ed638d842f23acd218cc06d71f1280f013f51112",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 256,
        "name": "Hiroya Nozaki",
        "email": "nozaki.hiroya@jp.fujitsu.com",
        "username": "HiroyaNozaki"
      },
      "date": "2012-06-11 10:18:25.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI had wondered why filter_cleanup() is executed while some exports still exist, and finally I realized that the refcount of export object is too low as expected. I mean this is not a problem of the race condition but a problem of export's refcount.\n\nI'll described the issue on Jira from now on. So could Bobi confirm the article there?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
